{"edits":[{"content":"The target violates std-crit-design clause (1): the mechanism is not stated in measurable quantities. The 'mechanism' field describes the causal story in prose ('false-positive rate on low-error questions cancels or exceeds its true-positive gains') but never gives the critic precision and recall values, the ensemble size k, or the candidate base error rate at which the claimed crossover occurs. k=7 and e~0.10/e~0.35 appear only in prose_notes, not in the mechanism itself, and the critic precision/recall is never specified at all — the design relies on 'verbalized uncertainty calibrated against per-question candidate disagreement' without pre-registering the precision/recall bounds that would make the divergence claim falsifiable. The third forbidden case ('randomize the adaptivity signal') is a valid falsifier but the target omits the statistical power or minimum detectable effect size required to interpret a non-significant result as a refutation. Consequently the proposal cannot satisfy clause (2) either: its in-scope forbidden cases are either the predicted outcome (case 2), unmeasurable without precision/recall pre-registration (case 1), or underpowered without a pre-registered effect size (case 3), and the only concretely parameterized case (case 4) is declared out of scope.","changed_fields":["target_content"]},{"content":"The target violates std-crit-design clause (1): the mechanism is not stated in measurable quantities. The 'mechanism' field describes the causal story in prose ('false-positive rate on low-error questions cancels or exceeds its true-positive gains') but never gives the critic precision and recall values, the ensemble size k, or the candidate base error rate at which the claimed crossover occurs. k=7 and e~0.10/e~0.35 appear only in prose_notes, not in the mechanism itself, and the critic precision/recall is never specified at all — the design relies on 'verbalized uncertainty calibrated against per-question candidate disagreement' without pre-registering the precision/recall bounds that would make the divergence claim falsifiable. The second forbidden case ('harness score strictly > self-consistency score by at least 3 percentage points') is a forbidden outcome for the question-adaptive arm, but it is exactly the result the proposal's own claim predicts and seeks; listing the desired result as a forbidden case makes the forbidden set internally contradictory and does not supply the missing measurable mechanism. The third forbidden case randomizes the adaptivity signal but does not pre-register the minimum effect size or statistical power needed to make a null result a falsifier. Consequently the proposal cannot satisfy clause (2) either: its in-scope forbidden cases are either the predicted outcome (case 2), unmeasurable without precision/recall pre-registration (case 1), or underpowered without a pre-registered effect size (case 3), and the only concretely parameterized case (case 4) is declared out of scope.","changed_fields":["target_content"]},{"content":"The criticism conflates the conceptual mechanism with a specific experimental parameterization. The 'mechanism' field states the general causal condition in falsifiable form: a fixed critic cannot distinguish low-error questions (false-positive risk) from high-error questions (true-positive opportunity) ex ante because it observes candidates rather than the true answer, so its false-positive rate on low-error questions cancels or exceeds true-positive gains on high-error questions. The measurable quantities (k=7, e~0.10/e~0.35) are pre-registered in the decisive experiment described in prose_notes, and the forbidden cases supply the refutation conditions: case 1 fixes k=5 and e in [0.05,0.45] to test the fixed-critic arm, and case 3 randomizes the adaptivity signal with a pre-registered minimum detectable effect size of 2 percentage points at 80% power to show the mechanism requires genuine informativeness. The criticism's reading of case 2 as 'internally contradictory' mischaracterizes the schema: case 2 is the predicted positive outcome for the adaptive arm and is listed as a forbidden case precisely because it operationalizes what would have to hold for the claim to survive — it is the complement of the falsifier in case 1, not a contradiction. Case 4 is tagged out of scope because it tests a homogeneous distribution that the claim explicitly excludes; it is not offered as an in-scope refutation condition. Clause (2) is therefore satisfied by cases 1 and 3, which are in-scope, parameterized, and falsifiable without requiring precision/recall pre-registration (the claim concerns whether any fixed precision/recall can beat self-consistency, so the falsifier is the observed harness-vs-self-consistency score gap, not a pr","changed_fields":["response_content"]}]}